      "seed": 1508381876,
      "version": 931,
      "versionNonce": 52711850,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742402680904,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Builder Pattern -\n    a. It focuses on constructing complex objects step by step.\n    b. The Builder interface would have APIs which would aid in constructing the final product.\n    c. It is useful in scenarios where a class needs to intake a bunch of parameters to construct its object\n       whereas it could be broken down to setter APIs of a interface responsible for building the object. \n    b. In the below example, Animal Builder could have been those bunch of parameters consumed by Animal Interface.\n    d. We can have a concrete class (called Dog) whose responsibility is to create an object  by correctly filling the Setter APIs.\n    e. We also have another class (Cat) who has the same responsibility but the values could be different.\n    f. Both of these classes can then extend the same Animal Interface and follow the factory pattern to vend out public APIs to client.\n    g. Client can only interact with Animal class Interface (Abstract class) because \n       the job of the concrete class (which is just to build the object) is over\n   ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Builder Pattern -\n    a. It focuses on constructing complex objects step by step.\n    b. The Builder interface would have APIs which would aid in constructing the final product.\n    c. It is useful in scenarios where a class needs to intake a bunch of parameters to construct its object\n       whereas it could be broken down to setter APIs of a interface responsible for building the object. \n    b. In the below example, Animal Builder could have been those bunch of parameters consumed by Animal Interface.\n    d. We can have a concrete class (called Dog) whose responsibility is to create an object  by correctly filling the Setter APIs.\n    e. We also have another class (Cat) who has the same responsibility but the values could be different.\n    f. Both of these classes can then extend the same Animal Interface and follow the factory pattern to vend out public APIs to client.\n    g. Client can only interact with Animal class Interface (Abstract class) because \n       the job of the concrete class (which is just to build the object) is over\n   ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
