      "y": 7867.901105491114,
      "width": 1707.5333251953125,
      "height": 364.7609775938975,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2u",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2087027446,
      "version": 4575,
      "versionNonce": 543926454,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742451021531,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n6. Facade Pattern - (Known as Orchestrator)\n   a. It is basically an orchestrator with the list of steps to invoke other classes (these classes may or may not extend the same interface) \n\n7. Composite Pattern -  (Creates Composition)\n   a. It is a list of concrete classes extending the same interface. However, the list can also contain another list of concrete classes, \n      where the another list extends the same interface.\n   b. In short, the composite class should also extend the same interface, portraying a tree like structure where non-leaf elements of \n      Level lesser than H - 1 (where H is the height and Level H contains leaf elements) is itself a composite class (which is a list)\n      and elements belonging to Level H-1 is a composite class containing concrete classes.\n   c. There is a slight similarity between composite and decorator where the clients interact with the top level class. However, the difference is \n       decorator will always have a Height 1 where composite will have height more than 1",
      "fontSize": 24.317398506259835,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n6. Facade Pattern - (Known as Orchestrator)\n   a. It is basically an orchestrator with the list of steps to invoke other classes (these classes may or may not extend the same interface) \n\n7. Composite Pattern -  (Creates Composition)\n   a. It is a list of concrete classes extending the same interface. However, the list can also contain another list of concrete classes, \n      where the another list extends the same interface.\n   b. In short, the composite class should also extend the same interface, portraying a tree like structure where non-leaf elements of \n      Level lesser than H - 1 (where H is the height and Level H contains leaf elements) is itself a composite class (which is a list)\n      and elements belonging to Level H-1 is a composite class containing concrete classes.\n   c. There is a slight similarity between composite and decorator where the clients interact with the top level class. However, the difference is \n       decorator will always have a Height 1 where composite will have height more than 1",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "o2qy1Pah5VtCdOoeNvG5J",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 547.7298101382959,
      "y": 5957.076047032668,
      "width": 1243.933349609375,
      "height": 364.7609775938975,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2v",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1765424298,
      "version": 3709,
      "versionNonce": 1021536361,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1765925563797,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n4. Proxy Pattern - \n   a. It is exactly similar to decorator pattern where your proxy class would extend the same interface, \n      which is being extended by the concrete class.\n   b. However, the twist is Proxy class will have an extra responsibility to make a decision whether to \n      call the concrete class or not.\n   b. Hence, the only difference between decorator and proxy class is that decorator will always call\n      the concrete class (in the above example, we always call Expresso's printCoffeeFlavor()). However,\n      proxy class will make a decision whether to call the concrete class.\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 24.317398506259835,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n4. Proxy Pattern - \n   a. It is exactly similar to decorator pattern where your proxy class would extend the same interface, \n      which is being extended by the concrete class.\n   b. However, the twist is Proxy class will have an extra responsibility to make a decision whether to \n      call the concrete class or not.\n   b. Hence, the only difference between decorator and proxy class is that decorator will always call\n      the concrete class (in the above example, we always call Expresso's printCoffeeFlavor()). However,\n      proxy class will make a decision whether to call the concrete class.\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
