      "versionNonce": 1357468726,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742451009002,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n2. Bridge Pattern - (Creates Composition)\n   a. It is useful when you want to divide your class into multiple dependent feature interfaces, \n      each having their own set of concrete implementations \n      (so you can do permutation and combination with those dependent interfaces)\n   b. It is slightly similar to Adapter pattern but the main difference is these interfaces in Bridge Pattern\n      are not wrapper over the another but dependent on each other.\n   c. In the below example, I segregated out the feature 'Sound' and 'AnimalBodyType' into 2 different interfaces\n      such that Client can only call AnimalBodyType interface where it can directly have a relationship with 'Sound' interface\n      and can complete the whole 'Animal' interface.\n   d. I have hard-coded 'Bark' in 'FourLegged' but there can also be a 'FourLegged' who squeaks \n      Hence, Sound can be passed as a param which would prevent me from creating another FourLeggedWithSqueak concrete class.\n",
      "fontSize": 24.317398506259835,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n2. Bridge Pattern - (Creates Composition)\n   a. It is useful when you want to divide your class into multiple dependent feature interfaces, \n      each having their own set of concrete implementations \n      (so you can do permutation and combination with those dependent interfaces)\n   b. It is slightly similar to Adapter pattern but the main difference is these interfaces in Bridge Pattern\n      are not wrapper over the another but dependent on each other.\n   c. In the below example, I segregated out the feature 'Sound' and 'AnimalBodyType' into 2 different interfaces\n      such that Client can only call AnimalBodyType interface where it can directly have a relationship with 'Sound' interface\n      and can complete the whole 'Animal' interface.\n   d. I have hard-coded 'Bark' in 'FourLegged' but there can also be a 'FourLegged' who squeaks \n      Hence, Sound can be passed as a param which would prevent me from creating another FourLeggedWithSqueak concrete class.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
