    {
      "id": "hnwVmG0ogc4KmYDpXuUUC",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1370.0153764324682,
      "y": 8428.269211164736,
      "width": 1419.63330078125,
      "height": 2750,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffffff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5K",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1310499690,
      "version": 7802,
      "versionNonce": 105327174,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742621871023,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Confusion between Similar patterns --> \n\n1. Adapter and Bridge Pattern - \n    a. Similarity - Both the patterns work with a minimum 2 incompatible interfaces\n    b. Distinction - \n         1. In Adapter pattern, the adapter is an interface used by client, which wraps\n            over the incompatible interface and internally call its API\n         2. In Bridge pattern, the top level interface used by clients calls another interface's API\n            with an intent to complete the objective rather than wrapping.\n\n\n2. Decorator and Proxy Pattern --\n    a. Similarity - Both the patterns have their concrete classes extends to the same interface.\n    b. Distinction - \n         1. In Decorator pattern, every decorator is a wrapper over another decorator\n            which in further wraps the actual leaf concrete class. In short, decorator pattern\n            always call the leaf concrete class, by adding extra behavior along the way.\n         2. In Proxy pattern, every proxy is a wrapper over another proxy which in further proxies\n            the actual leaf concrete class. However, every proxy has a critical responsibility to make\n            a decision on whether to call the other proxy/leaf concrete class or not.\n\n\n3. Proxy and Flyweight Pattern - \n    a. Similarity - Both the patterns have the critical responsibility to make\n       a decision on whether to call the actual leaf concrete class or not.\n    b. Distinction - \n        1. In proxy pattern, proxy concrete class extends the same interface as of leaf \n           concrete class.\n        2. In Flyweight pattern, flyweight class does not extend the same interface as of\n            leaf concrete class\n\n\n4. Decorator and Composition Pattern -\n     a. Similarity - Both of the patterns wraps over its children, ultimately wrapping over actual leaf\n        concrete class extending to the same interface, by adding extra behavior along the way\n     b. Distinction -\n           a. In Decorator pattern, the wrapper list is a linear chain.\n           b. In Composition patter, the wrapper list is a tree.\n\n\n5. Decorator and Chain of Responsibility Pattern -\n     a. Similarity - Both of the patterns forms a linear chain of steps, \n        where every step is aware of the next step.\n     b. Distinction -\n         a. In COR Pattern, every concrete class is a step by itself and \n           decides whether to call the next step or not.\n         b. In Decorator pattern, every decorator will eventually call other decorator which finally calls \n             the leaf concrete class (final step), by adding extra behavior along the way --> Composition\n\n\n6. Bridge and Composite Pattern -\n     a. Similarity - Both of these pattern performs composition to form a complex structure.\n     b. Distinction -\n        a. In Bridge, there are be many disjoint interfaces depending on each other to create a complex structure (M *N )\n        b. In Composite, the interface is 1 but tree grows to create all possible combination of leaf concrete classes.\n\n\n7. Visitor and Bridge Pattern - \n    a. Similarity - Both of these patterns involves communication between 2 interfaces \n    b. Distinction -\n         a. Bridge Pattern is used to create an object via composition having a combination of \n           M concrete classes of interface 1 and N concrete classes of interface 2.\n         b. In Visitor pattern, 1 interface needs to be stable and CLOSED whereas the other interface is tentative to grow\n            so that the other interface can conduct specific operations on the stable interface.\n\n8. Strategy and Visitor Pattern -\n    a. Similarity - Both of these patterns use an interface to conduct some type of operations on the client interface\n                     where client interface depends on the pattern interface.\n    b. Distinction - \n          a. In Strategy pattern, Client can select any one of the strategy concrete class during runtime \n             to conduct operations on its object.\n          b. In Visitor pattern,all visitor concrete class are mandatory operations to be conducted on the object\n\n\n9. Strategy and Bridge Pattern\n    a. Similarity - Both of these patterns require communication between 2 interfaces\n    b. Distinction - \n        a. Bridge Pattern is used to create an object via composition having a combination of \n           M concrete classes of interface 1 and N concrete classes of interface 2.\n        b. Strategy Pattern provides multiple options of conducting a specific operation on a client side object\n\n\n10. Facade and Command Pattern - \n     a. Similarity - Both the patterns is kind of orchestrator executing multiple steps line by line.\n     b. Distinction - \n          a. In Facade Pattern, all the steps will not extend the same interface\n          b. In Command Pattern, all the steps will extend the same interface \n\n\n11. Template and Command Pattern\n     a. Similarity - Both represents orchestration \n     b. Distinction -\n          a. In Command Pattern, the concrete classes are individual steps to perform a task together and sequence of steps is decided by client.\n          b. In Template Pattern, the interface creates a sequence of steps and concrete class is a task by itself which \n             implements/override the steps mentioned in the interface but cannot change the sequence of steps\n\n12. Observer and Mediator Pattern\n    a. Similarity: Both of these patterns act as mediator between 2 set of classes where 1 publish a message and other receives a message\n    b. Distinction -\n        a. In Observer pattern, the message is broadcasted to a group of subscribers and publisher is always 1\n        b. In Mediator pattern, the message is exchanged between 2 classes via a middle man to break circular dependency.\n\n\n\n            \n            \n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Confusion between Similar patterns --> \n\n1. Adapter and Bridge Pattern - \n    a. Similarity - Both the patterns work with a minimum 2 incompatible interfaces\n    b. Distinction - \n         1. In Adapter pattern, the adapter is an interface used by client, which wraps\n            over the incompatible interface and internally call its API\n         2. In Bridge pattern, the top level interface used by clients calls another interface's API\n            with an intent to complete the objective rather than wrapping.\n\n\n2. Decorator and Proxy Pattern --\n    a. Similarity - Both the patterns have their concrete classes extends to the same interface.\n    b. Distinction - \n         1. In Decorator pattern, every decorator is a wrapper over another decorator\n            which in further wraps the actual leaf concrete class. In short, decorator pattern\n            always call the leaf concrete class, by adding extra behavior along the way.\n         2. In Proxy pattern, every proxy is a wrapper over another proxy which in further proxies\n            the actual leaf concrete class. However, every proxy has a critical responsibility to make\n            a decision on whether to call the other proxy/leaf concrete class or not.\n\n\n3. Proxy and Flyweight Pattern - \n    a. Similarity - Both the patterns have the critical responsibility to make\n       a decision on whether to call the actual leaf concrete class or not.\n    b. Distinction - \n        1. In proxy pattern, proxy concrete class extends the same interface as of leaf \n           concrete class.\n        2. In Flyweight pattern, flyweight class does not extend the same interface as of\n            leaf concrete class\n\n\n4. Decorator and Composition Pattern -\n     a. Similarity - Both of the patterns wraps over its children, ultimately wrapping over actual leaf\n        concrete class extending to the same interface, by adding extra behavior along the way\n     b. Distinction -\n           a. In Decorator pattern, the wrapper list is a linear chain.\n           b. In Composition patter, the wrapper list is a tree.\n\n\n5. Decorator and Chain of Responsibility Pattern -\n     a. Similarity - Both of the patterns forms a linear chain of steps, \n        where every step is aware of the next step.\n     b. Distinction -\n         a. In COR Pattern, every concrete class is a step by itself and \n           decides whether to call the next step or not.\n         b. In Decorator pattern, every decorator will eventually call other decorator which finally calls \n             the leaf concrete class (final step), by adding extra behavior along the way --> Composition\n\n\n6. Bridge and Composite Pattern -\n     a. Similarity - Both of these pattern performs composition to form a complex structure.\n     b. Distinction -\n        a. In Bridge, there are be many disjoint interfaces depending on each other to create a complex structure (M *N )\n        b. In Composite, the interface is 1 but tree grows to create all possible combination of leaf concrete classes.\n\n\n7. Visitor and Bridge Pattern - \n    a. Similarity - Both of these patterns involves communication between 2 interfaces \n    b. Distinction -\n         a. Bridge Pattern is used to create an object via composition having a combination of \n           M concrete classes of interface 1 and N concrete classes of interface 2.\n         b. In Visitor pattern, 1 interface needs to be stable and CLOSED whereas the other interface is tentative to grow\n            so that the other interface can conduct specific operations on the stable interface.\n\n8. Strategy and Visitor Pattern -\n    a. Similarity - Both of these patterns use an interface to conduct some type of operations on the client interface\n                     where client interface depends on the pattern interface.\n    b. Distinction - \n          a. In Strategy pattern, Client can select any one of the strategy concrete class during runtime \n             to conduct operations on its object.\n          b. In Visitor pattern,all visitor concrete class are mandatory operations to be conducted on the object\n\n\n9. Strategy and Bridge Pattern\n    a. Similarity - Both of these patterns require communication between 2 interfaces\n    b. Distinction - \n        a. Bridge Pattern is used to create an object via composition having a combination of \n           M concrete classes of interface 1 and N concrete classes of interface 2.\n        b. Strategy Pattern provides multiple options of conducting a specific operation on a client side object\n\n\n10. Facade and Command Pattern - \n     a. Similarity - Both the patterns is kind of orchestrator executing multiple steps line by line.\n     b. Distinction - \n          a. In Facade Pattern, all the steps will not extend the same interface\n          b. In Command Pattern, all the steps will extend the same interface \n\n\n11. Template and Command Pattern\n     a. Similarity - Both represents orchestration \n     b. Distinction -\n          a. In Command Pattern, the concrete classes are individual steps to perform a task together and sequence of steps is decided by client.\n          b. In Template Pattern, the interface creates a sequence of steps and concrete class is a task by itself which \n             implements/override the steps mentioned in the interface but cannot change the sequence of steps\n\n12. Observer and Mediator Pattern\n    a. Similarity: Both of these patterns act as mediator between 2 set of classes where 1 publish a message and other receives a message\n    b. Distinction -\n        a. In Observer pattern, the message is broadcasted to a group of subscribers and publisher is always 1\n        b. In Mediator pattern, the message is exchanged between 2 classes via a middle man to break circular dependency.\n\n\n\n            \n            \n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Un2Ea5dflhEeN-yt_-SDf",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 564.6715183175609,
      "y": 11147.146725501609,
      "width": 1485.199951171875,
      "height": 455.9512219923719,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5L",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1310107498,
      "version": 4908,
      "versionNonce": 1042470186,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742447707770,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n3. Visitor Pattern -\n     a. It is useful to tackle use-cases when your interface keeps on growing due to addition of new operations\n        on stable object data.\n     b. For example - you have a list of products such as Clothing, Electronics and Books. However, operations \n        such as tax calculation, whether they are prime eligible or shipping cost keeps on getting added every month.\n     c. If this example would have been implemented as an interface which would define these operations and products\n        such as Clothing, Electronics and Books would extend the interface, everytime a new operation needs to be added\n        we have to modify the interface, which violates the OPEN/CLOSE principle.\n     d. With Visitor Pattern, we CLOSE the product Interface completely and create a Visitor Interface which would traverse\n        through the list of Products and conduct operations on them\n   \n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 24.317398506259835,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n3. Visitor Pattern -\n     a. It is useful to tackle use-cases when your interface keeps on growing due to addition of new operations\n        on stable object data.\n     b. For example - you have a list of products such as Clothing, Electronics and Books. However, operations \n        such as tax calculation, whether they are prime eligible or shipping cost keeps on getting added every month.\n     c. If this example would have been implemented as an interface which would define these operations and products\n        such as Clothing, Electronics and Books would extend the interface, everytime a new operation needs to be added\n        we have to modify the interface, which violates the OPEN/CLOSE principle.\n     d. With Visitor Pattern, we CLOSE the product Interface completely and create a Visitor Interface which would traverse\n        through the list of Products and conduct operations on them\n   \n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
