    {
      "id": "W9hlkFhudO00u8ZHDvsk7",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 544.384951703106,
      "y": 15217.710381969573,
      "width": 1592.5333251953125,
      "height": 638.3317107893207,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6m",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 94953347,
      "version": 7503,
      "versionNonce": 640867802,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742621575687,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n7. State Pattern -\n     a. The client class will use the state interface to maintain its own state. \n         The concrete classes of the state interface will be aware about its next state or previous state.\n     b. It is similar concept of Finite State Machine\n     c. The diagram in Refactoring guru is just too much as we won't be using the state pattern in production\n         exactly like the way mentioned in the website.\n\n8. Iterator Pattern -\n     a. It is basically traversal algorithm over a linear chain or a tree. \n     b. It is useful if your service needs to traverse through multiple classes extending the same interface (maybe composition)\n\n9. Observer Pattern -\n     a. There is a concrete publisher class which holds the object of all subscribers as subscribes needs to register themself\n     b. There is a subscriber interface which is extended by all subscribers\n     a. The invoker (Client1) uses a publisher class to sends a notification and the publisher class loops through its list of subscribers\n        and call the specific API to notify them.\n\n10. Memento Pattern -\n     a. It is useful when you need to create a snapshot of the current state of a class such that it can be restored later. \n",
      "fontSize": 24.317398506259835,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n7. State Pattern -\n     a. The client class will use the state interface to maintain its own state. \n         The concrete classes of the state interface will be aware about its next state or previous state.\n     b. It is similar concept of Finite State Machine\n     c. The diagram in Refactoring guru is just too much as we won't be using the state pattern in production\n         exactly like the way mentioned in the website.\n\n8. Iterator Pattern -\n     a. It is basically traversal algorithm over a linear chain or a tree. \n     b. It is useful if your service needs to traverse through multiple classes extending the same interface (maybe composition)\n\n9. Observer Pattern -\n     a. There is a concrete publisher class which holds the object of all subscribers as subscribes needs to register themself\n     b. There is a subscriber interface which is extended by all subscribers\n     a. The invoker (Client1) uses a publisher class to sends a notification and the publisher class loops through its list of subscribers\n        and call the specific API to notify them.\n\n10. Memento Pattern -\n     a. It is useful when you need to create a snapshot of the current state of a class such that it can be restored later. \n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "vShmILAiEqgXzSpoLDrMT",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 568.4123209507236,
      "y": 14447.339518537497,
      "width": 1409.1058650965226,
      "height": 210.1876320088785,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6n",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 87288838,
      "version": 7213,
      "versionNonce": 780015046,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1742621028534,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n6. Mediator Pattern -\n     a. It is useful if you don't want classes to be dependent upon each other, preferably making a circular dependency.  \n     b. It breaks circular dependency by acting as a middle man where both the classes are dependent on the middle man \n        and it propagates the request to both of them.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 24.02144365815756,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n6. Mediator Pattern -\n     a. It is useful if you don't want classes to be dependent upon each other, preferably making a circular dependency.  \n     b. It breaks circular dependency by acting as a middle man where both the classes are dependent on the middle man \n        and it propagates the request to both of them.\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
