    {
      "id": "J8qaXiWW8UfZGD5X8nj8O",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1257.711216027006,
      "y": 5411.006605702016,
      "width": 1568.5,
      "height": 1075,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b77",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1755871431,
      "version": 3082,
      "versionNonce": 1623821575,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1765929263917,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Low-Level Design Approach - \n\n1. Figuring out the requirements of the Problem - \n      a. Primary capabilities — What operations must this system support?\n      b. Rules and completion — What conditions define success, failure, or when the system stops or transitions state?\n      c. Error handling — How should the system respond when inputs or actions are invalid?\n      d. Scope boundaries — What areas are in scope (core logic, business rules) and what areas are explicitly out (UI, storage, networking, concurrency, extensibility)?\n2. Identify Entities and Relationships.\n3. For every Entity - lets figure out the state and behavior (methods) it needs to own. \n         a. These needs to be figured out from the requirements that we gathered from Step #1.\n         b. We will use this to model the Entity Class.\n4. Start with a happy path and then worry about edge cases.\n\n\nOOP Principles - \n   1. Single Responsibility Principle - Each Entity should have just 1 responsibility. If there are multiple responsibilities, there is an opportunity to break up the entity.\n   2. Open/Close Principle - Open for Extension but closed for modification - Usually inheritance or composition helps to solve this principle\n   3. Interface Segregation Principle - If the concrete classes are overriding less than 30% of the methods exposed by interface, it is better to break up the interface.\n   4. Dependency Inversion Principle - If an entity can be substituted, hide it behind an interface and use that interface in another modules to communicate. \n          a. For Example - Notification Service can use a Message Sender interface whose concrete classes can be Email Sender. In future, we need to substitute Email\n              Sender with Phone Message Sender or Whatsapp Sender, we can just update passing the concrete class to Notification Service without changing Notification Service.\n          b. Here EmailSender, Phone Message Sender, Whatsapp Sender are all polymorphism candidates\n              and NotificationService using Message Sender is an example of Composition.\n   5. Composition over Inheritance - Don't force an entity to extend an interface. Think if that entity can be formed by - \n            a. Extending multiple Interfaces -> \n                     class SmartPhone extends Camera, Phone, MediaPlayer, GPS {\n                              public takePhoto() {\n                                        /** Add logic on how to take photo */ extended from Camera Interface\n                              }\n                     }\n            b. Creating a composition --> An entity with a combination of multiple interfaces\n                     class SmartPhone {\n                             SmartPhone(Camera camera, Phone phone, MediaPlayer media, GPS gps){\n                                    this.m_camera = camera;\n                              }\n                            \n                              public takePhoto() {\n                                       m_camera.takePhoto(); // This Camera is already an concrete class (Say Apple Designated Camera)\n                                       // In Option A, you have to implement the logic of Apple Designated Camera\n                              }\n                              \n                      }\n ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Low-Level Design Approach - \n\n1. Figuring out the requirements of the Problem - \n      a. Primary capabilities — What operations must this system support?\n      b. Rules and completion — What conditions define success, failure, or when the system stops or transitions state?\n      c. Error handling — How should the system respond when inputs or actions are invalid?\n      d. Scope boundaries — What areas are in scope (core logic, business rules) and what areas are explicitly out (UI, storage, networking, concurrency, extensibility)?\n2. Identify Entities and Relationships.\n3. For every Entity - lets figure out the state and behavior (methods) it needs to own. \n         a. These needs to be figured out from the requirements that we gathered from Step #1.\n         b. We will use this to model the Entity Class.\n4. Start with a happy path and then worry about edge cases.\n\n\nOOP Principles - \n   1. Single Responsibility Principle - Each Entity should have just 1 responsibility. If there are multiple responsibilities, there is an opportunity to break up the entity.\n   2. Open/Close Principle - Open for Extension but closed for modification - Usually inheritance or composition helps to solve this principle\n   3. Interface Segregation Principle - If the concrete classes are overriding less than 30% of the methods exposed by interface, it is better to break up the interface.\n   4. Dependency Inversion Principle - If an entity can be substituted, hide it behind an interface and use that interface in another modules to communicate. \n          a. For Example - Notification Service can use a Message Sender interface whose concrete classes can be Email Sender. In future, we need to substitute Email\n              Sender with Phone Message Sender or Whatsapp Sender, we can just update passing the concrete class to Notification Service without changing Notification Service.\n          b. Here EmailSender, Phone Message Sender, Whatsapp Sender are all polymorphism candidates\n              and NotificationService using Message Sender is an example of Composition.\n   5. Composition over Inheritance - Don't force an entity to extend an interface. Think if that entity can be formed by - \n            a. Extending multiple Interfaces -> \n                     class SmartPhone extends Camera, Phone, MediaPlayer, GPS {\n                              public takePhoto() {\n                                        /** Add logic on how to take photo */ extended from Camera Interface\n                              }\n                     }\n            b. Creating a composition --> An entity with a combination of multiple interfaces\n                     class SmartPhone {\n                             SmartPhone(Camera camera, Phone phone, MediaPlayer media, GPS gps){\n                                    this.m_camera = camera;\n                              }\n                            \n                              public takePhoto() {\n                                       m_camera.takePhoto(); // This Camera is already an concrete class (Say Apple Designated Camera)\n                                       // In Option A, you have to implement the logic of Apple Designated Camera\n                              }\n                              \n                      }\n ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
  ],
